  "prompt": "Education system of India before the arrival of Britishers?",
  "response": "Before the arrival of the British, India had a well-established and diverse education system:\n\n1. Traditional Education Systems:\n- Gurukul System\n- Pathshala (Hindu traditional schools)\n- Maktabs and Madrasas (Muslim educational institutions)\n\n2. Gurukul System:\n- Religious and spiritual education\n- Residential learning\n- Free education\n- Focus on holistic development\n- Subjects included Vedas, Sanskrit, mathematics, philosophy\n\n3. Pathashalas:\n- Village-level schools\n- Teaching Sanskrit, regional languages\n- Emphasis on religious and cultural knowledge\n- Supported by local communities\n\n4. Madrasas:\n- Islamic educational institutions\n- Teaching Quran, Arabic, Persian\n- Subjects included mathematics, astronomy, philosophy\n- Prevalent during Mughal period\n\n5. Specialized Learning Centers:\n- Nalanda University\n- Takshashila University\n- Advanced learning in various disciplines\n- International students\n- Subjects included medicine, mathematics, astronomy, philosophy\n\n6. Patronage:\n- Supported by rulers, wealthy merchants\n- Temple and mosque-based education\n- Community-driven learning\n\n7. Learning Approach:\n- Oral transmission of knowledge\n- Guru-Shishya (teacher-student) tradition\n- Personalized learning\n- Skill-based education\n\nThese systems were comprehensive and culturally rooted before British colonial education was introduced.",
